<section id="male-risk">
    <h2>Why Men Are at Higher Risk for Heart Attacks</h2>

    <p>Heart disease is the leading cause of death for men in the United States, killing approximately <strong>1 in 4 men</strong>. Men are twice as likely as women to have a heart attack and tend to have them <strong>10-15 years earlier</strong>.</p>

    <div class="key-point">
        <h3>Key Statistics: Men and Heart Disease</h3>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>382,776</strong> men die from heart disease annually in the US</li>
            <li><strong>1 in 4</strong> male deaths is from heart disease</li>
            <li><strong>50%</strong> of men who die suddenly from heart disease had no previous symptoms</li>
            <li><strong>28</strong> years old - youngest heart attack patient in our practice</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <h3>The Biological Factors</h3>
    <p>Several biological differences put men at higher cardiovascular risk:</p>

    <ul>
        <li><strong>Lower estrogen levels:</strong> Estrogen helps maintain arterial flexibility and healthy cholesterol profiles. Men lack this natural protection.</li>
        <li><strong>Visceral fat patterns:</strong> Men store fat around organs (visceral fat) rather than subcutaneously, creating more inflammation and metabolic dysfunction.</li>
        <li><strong>Higher insulin resistance rates:</strong> The male pattern of central obesity correlates with more severe insulin resistance.</li>
        <li><strong>Larger hearts:</strong> Men's hearts work harder, pumping more blood and creating more demand on coronary arteries.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Behavioral Risk Factors More Common in Men</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>Higher rates of smoking (historically)</li>
        <li>Greater alcohol consumption</li>
        <li>Less likely to seek medical care</li>
        <li>Higher stress response to work and financial pressures</li>
        <li>Less likely to report symptoms or discuss health concerns</li>
    </ul>
</section>

<section id="warning-signs">
    <h2>Warning Signs of Heart Attack in Men</h2>

    <p>Men typically experience "classic" heart attack symptoms more often than women, but many ignore early warning signs for days or weeks before a major event.</p>

    <div class="warning-box">
        <h3>Classic Heart Attack Symptoms in Men</h3>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Chest pain or pressure:</strong> Often described as "an elephant sitting on my chest" - the most common symptom</li>
            <li><strong>Radiating pain:</strong> Pain spreading to left arm, shoulder, jaw, neck, or back</li>
            <li><strong>Shortness of breath:</strong> With or without chest discomfort</li>
            <li><strong>Cold sweats:</strong> Breaking into a sweat without exertion</li>
            <li><strong>Nausea or vomiting:</strong> Often mistaken for indigestion</li>
            <li><strong>Lightheadedness:</strong> Feeling faint or dizzy</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <h3>The "Silent" Heart Attack Problem</h3>
    <p>Approximately <strong>1 in 5 heart attacks are silent</strong> - meaning they occur with minimal or no symptoms. These are particularly dangerous because:</p>
    <ul>
        <li>No treatment is sought during the event</li>
        <li>Heart muscle dies without intervention</li>
        <li>Often only discovered later on ECG or imaging</li>
        <li>Each silent heart attack increases risk of subsequent events</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="key-point">
        <h3>Early Warning Signs (Days to Weeks Before)</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>Unusual fatigue during normal activities</li>
            <li>Sleep disturbances</li>
            <li>Erectile dysfunction (vascular early warning)</li>
            <li>Shortness of breath climbing stairs</li>
            <li>Chest discomfort during physical exertion</li>
            <li>Indigestion that doesn't respond to antacids</li>
        </ul>
    </div>
</section>

