<section id="testosterone">
    <h2>The Testosterone-Heart Disease Connection</h2>

    <p>Testosterone levels in men have declined by approximately <strong>1% per year</strong> since the 1980s. This decline is linked to both heart disease risk and the metabolic dysfunction that causes it.</p>

    <h3>Low Testosterone and Cardiovascular Risk</h3>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Metabolic syndrome:</strong> Low T is strongly associated with insulin resistance, obesity, and elevated blood sugar</li>
        <li><strong>Inflammation:</strong> Low testosterone correlates with higher inflammatory markers (CRP, IL-6)</li>
        <li><strong>Arterial stiffness:</strong> Testosterone helps maintain arterial elasticity</li>
        <li><strong>Visceral fat:</strong> Low T promotes abdominal fat accumulation</li>
        <li><strong>Clotting factors:</strong> Suboptimal testosterone may affect clotting cascade</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="key-point">
        <h3>The Chicken-and-Egg Problem</h3>
        <p>Insulin resistance CAUSES low testosterone, and low testosterone WORSENS insulin resistance. This creates a vicious cycle:</p>
        <ol>
            <li>Poor diet and lifestyle → insulin resistance</li>
            <li>Insulin resistance → increased visceral fat</li>
            <li>Visceral fat → aromatase enzyme converts testosterone to estrogen</li>
            <li>Lower testosterone → more insulin resistance</li>
            <li>Cycle continues → heart disease develops</li>
        </ol>
    </div>

    <h3>Testosterone Warning Signs</h3>
    <p>These symptoms may indicate low testosterone and increased cardiovascular risk:</p>
    <ul>
        <li>Decreased energy and motivation</li>
        <li>Increased body fat, especially around the midsection</li>
        <li>Reduced muscle mass and strength</li>
        <li>Erectile dysfunction</li>
        <li>Depression or mood changes</li>
        <li>Poor sleep quality</li>
    </ul>

    <p><strong>Important:</strong> Address the root cause (insulin resistance) before considering testosterone replacement. Many men see testosterone normalize after metabolic health improves.</p>
</section>

<section id="silent-killers">
    <h2>The Silent Killers: Risk Factors Men Ignore</h2>

    <p>Men are notorious for ignoring health warning signs. These "silent killers" often have no symptoms until it's too late:</p>

    <h3>1. High Blood Pressure (Hypertension)</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>Called the "silent killer" - often no symptoms</li>
        <li>Affects <strong>47%</strong> of American men</li>
        <li>Only 1 in 4 have it under control</li>
        <li>Every 20 mmHg increase doubles heart attack risk</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>2. Insulin Resistance</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>Present 10+ years before diabetes diagnosis</li>
        <li>Affects an estimated <strong>88%</strong> of American adults</li>
        <li>Standard tests don't catch it early</li>
        <li><strong>50% of heart attack patients are pre-diabetic, not diabetic</strong></li>
    </ul>

    <h3>3. Sleep Apnea</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>Affects <strong>25%</strong> of men (most undiagnosed)</li>
        <li>Increases heart attack risk by 30%</li>
        <li>Causes repeated oxygen drops during sleep</li>
        <li>Strongly linked to hypertension and arrhythmias</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>4. Chronic Inflammation</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>No obvious symptoms</li>
        <li>hs-CRP test reveals hidden inflammation</li>
        <li>Driven by diet, stress, poor sleep, obesity</li>
        <li>Directly damages arterial walls</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>5. Erectile Dysfunction</h3>
    <div class="warning-box">
        <p><strong>ED is a cardiovascular warning sign.</strong> The penile arteries are smaller than coronary arteries, so they clog first. ED often precedes heart attacks by 3-5 years. If you have ED, get cardiovascular screening immediately.</p>
    </div>
</section>

<section id="prevention">
    <h2>Heart Attack Prevention Protocol for Men</h2>

    <p>Based on 35 years of clinical cardiology and over 30,000 procedures, here's the evidence-based prevention protocol:</p>

    <h3>Phase 1: Know Your Numbers (This Month)</h3>
    <ol>
        <li><strong>Coronary Artery Calcium (CAC) Score:</strong> The single best predictor of heart attack risk. If it's zero, you're safe for now.</li>
        <li><strong>Fasting Insulin:</strong> Should be below 5 μIU/mL. Above 10 is danger zone.</li>
        <li><strong>Advanced Lipid Panel:</strong> LDL particle count and size matter more than total LDL.</li>
        <li><strong>hs-CRP:</strong> Inflammation marker - should be below 1.0 mg/L.</li>
        <li><strong>Testosterone (free and total):</strong> Check if you have symptoms of low T.</li>
        <li><strong>Blood Pressure:</strong> Know your numbers - should be under 120/80.</li>
    </ol>

    <h3>Phase 2: Address Root Causes (Months 1-3)</h3>
    <ol>
        <li><strong>Implement time-restricted eating:</strong> Start with 16:8 fasting window</li>
        <li><strong>Eliminate processed foods:</strong> Especially seed oils and refined carbs</li>
        <li><strong>Prioritize sleep:</strong> 7-8 hours minimum, treat sleep apnea if present</li>
        <li><strong>Add resistance training:</strong> Builds muscle, improves insulin sensitivity</li>
        <li><strong>Manage stress:</strong> Chronic stress elevates cortisol and insulin</li>
    </ol>

    <h3>Phase 3: Optimize and Monitor (Ongoing)</h3>
    <ol>
        <li><strong>Progress fasting:</strong> Consider 18:6 or OMAD based on results</li>
        <li><strong>Track biomarkers:</strong> Retest insulin, lipids every 3-6 months</li>
        <li><strong>Consider supplements:</strong> K2, Omega-3, Magnesium based on testing</li>
        <li><strong>Repeat CAC:</strong> Every 3-5 years to track progression</li>
    </ol>
</section>

<section id="emergency">
    <h2>Emergency Response: What to Do During a Heart Attack</h2>

    <div class="warning-box">
        <h3>If You Suspect a Heart Attack - ACT FAST</h3>
        <ol>
            <li><strong>Call 911 immediately</strong> - Don't drive yourself</li>
            <li><strong>Chew an aspirin</strong> (325mg) if not allergic - helps prevent clotting</li>
            <li><strong>Sit or lie down</strong> in a comfortable position</li>
            <li><strong>Loosen tight clothing</strong></li>
            <li><strong>Stay calm</strong> and wait for emergency services</li>
        </ol>
    </div>

    <h3>Time Is Muscle</h3>
    <p>During a heart attack, every minute without blood flow kills heart muscle cells. The phrase "time is muscle" reflects this reality:</p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Within 30 minutes:</strong> Heart cells begin to die</li>
        <li><strong>After 2 hours:</strong> Significant permanent damage</li>
        <li><strong>After 6 hours:</strong> Extensive irreversible damage</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Getting treatment within 90 minutes of symptom onset dramatically improves survival and reduces lasting damage.</strong></p>
</section>

